    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="593"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d593">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 341.115P51/51</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 21, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1596. Your 2120.<note n="1" xml:id="d593fn1">Not printed</note>. With reference
                    to statement in your telegram that Foreign Office has informed you suspicious
                    conduct of steamer <persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Joseph W. Fordney</hi>
                    </persName> in endeavoring to elude British patrol boat has tended to confirm
                    evidence cargo was intended for Germany, you may inform British Government
                    persons interested in vessel haying previously been informed regarding this
                    allegation, have transmitted to Department affidavit of captain of vessel to the
                    effect that he made no effort to evade British patrol ship, and that no other
                    officer at any time said anything to him indicating that he had not obeyed
                    orders promptly or had not been absolutely frank in his statements.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
